segments.text: What the guy from Oklahoma is Dean Kamm.
Where does Hannigan fit into this?
Well, Hannigan came while Earl Rutter was president.
Now, I had moved up from my job to what they called the Director of Student Services.
Yeah.
Director of Student Affairs.
No.
Director of Civilian Student Affairs.
And I moved the office to the Y, and I had, they called me, the rest of them called me the super counselor.
And somewhere along in this time, Earl Rudder brought Jim Hannigan here, and I'm trying to come up with a year, because Earl died in, what, 60?
No, he dies in 70.
He dies in 70.
So Jim Hannigan came here,
Mr. Rutter, the inauguration of Mr. Rutter is in early calendar 1960, but he had become president in 59.
And the inauguration is the next year.
And Hannigan gets... Rutter tells this story.
that he went to the computer and asked to find the best qualified general for being the dean of students.
Now, he wanted some military experience, but that was not it.
That's how he found Hannigan.
That's how Hannigan's name showed up.
Now, there may have been some others, but he showed up.
As you look back on it, how well did Hannigan understand A&M?
Well, of course, when he first came here, now he was a graduate of West Point, graduated there in 1926, same year, 29, same year Benny Zinn graduated from A&M.
He knew something about him, but it didn't take him long to learn it.
And he took copious notes and hardly ever, ever lost his temper.
with anybody.
And he was named dean of students.
Wasn't long after that, they hired another guy and they made him associate dean of students.
And he didn't pan out, so they moved me into his associate dean of students.
So you reported to Hannigan?
I reported to Hannigan.
We became very good friends.
And he retired, I guess, in 73.
Hannigan, do you have anything else on Hannigan?
No, no, I'd love to.
Hannigan, we knew he was going to retire.
We wanted to find a replacement for him because we knew they were going to make it a vice president's office.
And it had to be a Ph.D., which left me out, which I wouldn't mind.
And we belonged to an outfit called SWASPA, the Southwestern Association of Student Personnel Administrators.
And we went to the convention in Waco and I had known and Dean Hannigan had known
John Colas for some time, and so we talked about him.
Jim Hannigan and I talked about him on the way up there.
So he said, well, see if he's interested.
So I asked John, would you be interested in coming to A&M?
He was at East Texas at the time.
He said, you bet.
So I told Hannigan, and Hannigan offered him a chance to come down and interview, and so he's the only one.
I remember being one of the people that had lunch with John Colas when he came to visit and remember a nice pleasant impression that he made.
Let's go back to the Rutter years though.
How well did Mr. Rutter understand the students of the 60s?
Well, I think you may understand he just couldn't tolerate it.
He was not going to have any demonstrations on the campus.
And the funny thing about it was that the civilian students would tell the cadets to stay out of it, we'll handle it, because if the cadets get into it, then you've got the media down.
And, you know, he confronted these guys that wanted to march and everything and made them march around.
And they were having a confrontation in front of Sully one time.
And these civilian students told the Corps to go on back, well, about supper time.
And there was an NBC television crew were filming this.
And all they got is these civilian students telling these, what were they?
The ragtag group, they had a name.
and telling them off, and all of a sudden they hear the cadets marching to supper, and they're yelling as they enter the dining hall.
While I'm coming there, there's a riot on the other end of the campus.
Boy, they shut down those cameras, and they got down there.
Of course, all these kids marching, but then that time the civilian students told these guys, right now, get off the campus.
We don't want you here.
Is that the worst demonstration you remember in the 60s?
I don't remember any.
Well, they were going to march front time, and I think it was, I don't remember what it was about, but they met them at the north gate and wouldn't let them on the campus.

Civilian students made them walk down what's now a Welborn Road, and the police wouldn't let them walk on the road, so they had to walk in a ditch, and there was a little church down there in College Station over close to the railroad track that they were going to for a meeting.
What was their cause?
Do you remember?
Well, I don't know.
Of course, the Vietnam War wasn't going on then.
Well, it may have been.
When did the Vietnam War start, 61?
Well, no.
It may have been.
You were at Fort Polk in 61.
Yeah, but that was You're just trying to think about when it
I came back in 63, so it was sometime after 63.
Stay with Mr. Rutter.
What were his chief frustrations with student life?
What did he worry most about?
Well, he worried most about their appearances.
He didn't worry too much about the cadets, but he worried about the civilian appearances.
He also worried about the faculty appearances, too.
He wanted the kids to get an education.
Now, they brought a black in.
He'd come out of prison, but he had been a war hero.
And he came to A&M.
They got him in A&M somehow.
Earl Rudd accepted him, and he moved into one of the dorms I supervised then.
And he was one that he would occasionally call
one of the so-called counselors, and say, I'm coming out tonight.
I want to tour the dormitories.
And he'd go through, and he'd visit with them.
Well, he wanted to visit this black man.
He called me, and it was raining.
So I alerted the dorm data that we were coming.
When we get to this guy's room, there's no lights on except one little light in that room and a radio playing.
That's what they call it, soul music then.
And there were about four blacks in there.
And everybody turned the lights on, and I turned them on for them.
And he said, what's bothering you all?
Well, they had all kinds of things.
And he said, well, you're getting a good education.
Well, yeah, they thought.
He said, well, now this is just kind of like a filling station.
We're brought here to get a good education.
If you don't think you're getting it, I want to know.
Other stuff you can talk to somebody else about, but I want to know if you're not getting an education.
But he made the dormitories pretty regular.
Do you remember any student efforts to play any pranks or march on Mr. Rutter's house?
I don't remember him trying to march on his house, but he had a bulldog called Ranger and
If somebody wanted him to get a message, they'd paint that poor dog up, and that dog would go home to eat, of course.
And that's the way they got the messages to him.
But the only march that I remember where they marched on the president's home was when Jack Williams was president.
Were you, by chance, near the campus or on campus when Mr. Rutter's house burned, the president's house, over across from Sbisa?
I don't think so.
I've heard stories about it, but I don't remember when that house burned.
It was late on a Saturday, I believe.
Yeah.
All right, let's see.
Were you aware of Mr. Rutter's declining health before he goes to the hospital and dies?
Well, to a large degree, yes.
We knew that he left when he got nervous.
he'd eat, and he was on a mashed potato circuit at a lot of places, and he would get so overweight that he'd go to Houston to a hospital down there to lose weight.
Now, that's about as much as I knew about his medical history.
So when he passed away, of course he was in the hospital when he died, but we were all very surprised by it.
All right, let's see.
Evaluate Rutter as a president from the student life aspect.
Well, from the student life aspect, he was a good president.
A lot of the kids didn't like him, but they respected him because he made them
you know, get a haircut.
If they didn't get a haircut, well, he was after them.
And beards were out.
And they had to keep their dress proper.
I mean, when I say proper, they didn't have to wear a coat and tie or even a tie, but they better not walk around barefooted, you know.
And we wouldn't let them in our office if they were barefooted.
But I think he was pretty well liked.
I know a lot of the faculty really didn't like him, but
I don't know whether it was fear or what, but they respected him, you know.
You said barefoot student.
If a student came to your office barefooted, what did you say to him?
Go back to your room and put on your shoes and socks.
What if he came with a beard?
Go shave.
What if a student said, I'm not going to shave?
You can't talk to me.
Did anybody ever try to?
No, because they always had to come see me about something, see.
Those guys did.
What were the primary worries that you had to deal with from the students?
Well, we were concerned about keeping the dorms where they could study, and that the dormitory was clean, and presumably no alcohol, because we...
We didn't go into that in the civilian areas as much as we did in the Corps.
And we were concerned that they stayed in school and that they took care of their personal debts.
During your years in student life, did the use of alcohol on campus increase?
I don't think so.
We sponsored a lot of dances.
And I can't remember them coming to the dances, you know, enumerated.
Can you?
Yeah, they did toward the last.
They liked to have bands that came in with just the best songs, Sloppy Pants.
The music was so loud and so terrible.
But they were still dressed when they came in.
Yeah, there toward the end, it was pretty much, you know, they did their rights.
What about drugs?
Were there drugs being used on the campus during those years?
There may have been, but I didn't know about it.
I've heard about something.
I heard about some of them, smoking pot primarily.
Now women are admitted during the 60s under Mr. Rutter.
How did that change the task of a student counselor?
Well, really very little because they didn't live on the campus the first time.
And once they moved on the campus, I remember where the first dorm they moved in.
Was it Hart Hall?
Was that the first dorm they had?
No, it's one right there at Northgate.
Okay, that's Walton Hall, I guess.
All right, then that leads us to a new president.
When do you remember first encountering Jack Williams?
What was your first impression?
Well, first impression, you're not an Aggie.
That's off the bat.
But I began to like him, and I liked what he did.
He was an educator, for one thing.
Earl Rudder had laid the groundwork for the growth of A&M, but he kept it up.
And then about not long after he was president was when streaking became a vogue.
And we had some streakers on the campus and we caught them one night.
And I say we caught them, the university campus security then took pictures of them and
Well, the kids were so embarrassed.
But anyway, they were going to be dismissed from A&M.
And so some of the kids decided they were going to march on President Williams' home.
And John Coldis had gone to a convention.
And he had a dean of students, which was a guy by the name of Powell.
So I heard, because I'm an associate vice president then, I had heard that these kids were coming out, because somebody came and said they were going to march on President Williams' house.
So I alerted the University Police, and I hailed it and got down there.
Well, there was a pretty good crowd, and they were yelling and they were screaming and straggling and all, and Jack Williams comes out and he said, I'm going to talk to Williams.
Just stay in the house for a while.
Don't say anything to them.
Let me talk to them.
He said, I want to talk to them.
Well, they kind of shouted him down.
And so he finally did go back in.
And I finally convinced them they should leave.
And the university police came up to them.
They were writing names and everything else.
And they knew the kids that they were protesting to get out of school were going.
Their protest failed.
And that's the only one I can recall where they
Dr. Williams have a sense of humor?
Yeah, it was a, it was a, you kind of had to look for it once in a while.
I think the one famous one I can remember was when they said, you know what a hell of a Lou Koneck is, and he said, yeah, beat the hell out of Texas.
And they give him a, another time they gave him the horn sitting there, and he said, yeah, that's a careless carpenter.
What about his public speaking ability?
He was pretty good.
And then it's under him that John Coldis comes in.
Does Coldis change student life focus at all?
Well, the biggest change he made was that he wanted services in everything.
Coldest was the vice president for student services.
The business office was the business services office.
Everything had a service in it.
So that food service and all was under him, would be moved under him?
No, food service did not.
That stayed under the fiscal office.
Oh, okay, all right.
Well, eventually it went under him, though, didn't it?
Who?
Eventually, food services did go under.
I don't remember food services ever coming under John.
Describe Coltus as a man to work with and work for.
He was very easy to work for.
He just hated like the dickens to say no.
And I'd always tell him, you know, sometimes you need to say no.
And he said, I'm going to let you tell them no, which I did lots of times.
And I told everybody, I said, I wear the black hat, John.
But his door was always open to the students.
He'd come to work about 6.30 or so in the morning, and that's when he'd do his work, because at 8 o'clock he started.
A student could make an appointment with Colas at just about any time, unless he was in a meeting or something.
And he had an infallible memory for students' names.
Oh, my God.
He and his wife both.
Doris and I used to marvel when we'd go to the convention, because on the way back, they would talk to one another, and they would
we found out how they were doing this, they would remember something particular about that individual that they could associate with, and they would use their names constantly.
And they'd file it away.
Let's see.
As I understand it, one of Dr. Williams' conditions for his accepting the presidency here was that the board authorize him to designate a dorm
January of 1971 to be used for women.
So the female enrollment really goes upward.
Did that make much change in y'all's duties?
No.
They had, well, I'll take that back.
They had a dean of men, and they hired a woman who was a dean of women.
Who was that?
Toby Shriver.
Shriver.
But she got married.
Was that her name before she?
No, she got married several times.
I don't remember.
That was her name when she came.
Anyway, Hannigan, I was under Hannigan, wasn't I?
I was under Hannigan.
I was before Colas that she came.
So that worked out.
And she had an assistant that worked for her.
And they didn't have, they hired students
They didn't have somebody to go in and take their students, women students did that.
As you look back on these years when you were a key person in student life, of what are you most proud personally?
Well, I'm proud of the fact that

I think I did a good job and the students still, I see students all the time and they remember me when they come back and I kept a number of students in school that might not have been in school and I think I also kept, helped keep a hand on the discipline of the students.
We had pretty strong discipline up until this, shortly before I retired, on how we handled the students.
This is not under Colas, but it was under Hannigan.
I can remember they, they would come over here and was going to protest, and I guess that was the Vietnam War, and they had a bunch of students over there, and they were haranguing the students, and
O.L.
Luther was a Texas Ranger, and Jim Hannigan said, I want those guys in my office.
So he and Shorty Maddox, they've shouldered their way through the crowd, and I mean, they put their arm on this guy right there.
He and his friend, they were students, and brought him into Hannigan's office, and he said, you're out of school right now.
pack your stuff and leave because you're no longer enrolled at Texas A&M University.
That was about six o'clock in the evening.
I can remember, well I think I helped a lot on the discipline on the things.
I think I helped a lot of students.
Do you remember any student problems relating to race?
Race.
Race or ethnicity?
There was a couple of, on race, we had a few blacks, and they came to see, this was when I was director of civilian student activities.
They came to see me, about four of them one time, and they wanted to know, they wanted to complain about them, that they weren't being treated right, and they said,
One of the things they said was, you don't understand what it's like to be black.
And I said, I understand that.
But one thing you don't understand is to be a white when some of this stuff is being forced on you.
You want something to happen to your family or something might happen to you?
I said, don't threaten me.
That was the end of that conversation.
That's the only thing.
They complained about something, but I never heard the students complain about it.
But right after that, you got a call from campus police.
They were burning books over at the library.
Yeah.
But there were no, by and large, there had been no dormitory incidents.
Not that I know of.
Of black and white.
Not contrary.
They lived in there, you know, in the civilian dorms.
That was on the rudder.
All right, I'm almost through.
What have we not talked about?
What are the omissions?
What have we not talked about that we should have regarding?
Well, I think this was during part of the time when Dolores was working out there and I was with the guard.
Tell me about the office where you'd have, and I was in office, stayed open 24 hours a day.
And she worked on a weekend, on some weekends, and she was out there all day, Saturday and Sunday.
They just did everything.
I felt like we never had any time off because we had to learn telegraphy because they closed down over at the MSC, you know, during the holidays.
Western Union closed down.
But anyway, it was... And running messengers with telephone messages to come to the phone or call their parents or call a prof. We went on a cruise.
Last year, and there happened to be one of the boys that needed a job so badly, and he was one of my messengers, and he really climbed up to be an executive of a big oil company.
He was on this cruise.
When he saw me, he said, you know, he said, when I started working with you, he said, I thought you were going to be so easy.
He said, the first day I came to work, he said, it was pouring down rain.

and you had a lot of messages a lot of telephone calls you said to me bill you better get ready to deliver these and then he said miss perry it's raining and she does you knew when you were hired that you were going to have to work and do this there's a slicker and there's the bicycle so deliver it and when we got off the ship he hollered down said
Miss Berry, do you have any more messages?
But when the dorms were so crowded and we were having so much trouble placing all these students coming in and we had a three and four-door room.
And I always worried about so many times the students would forget to turn in their registration card.
And I had a call from the registrar's office and I couldn't find a...
I had on my roster the name Chanel.
But I couldn't find any registration or anything, so I finally called the first sergeant in.
And I got along with the students very well.
And he said, Miss Perry, he said, you know, we have a pet skunk in that room that's got little ones.
And I said, well, you get rid of it.
That was Chanel.
That was Chanel.
Had a room to herself.
and there were a lot of sad times with the students.
You don't remember students, you don't think of them really being poor at that time.
But there really were some that really just didn't have any money.
And I wasn't supposed to, but I did let them reserve their rooms, and I kept a lot of it up in my head.
I couldn't afford to take sick a lot of time during that time.
But anyway, the students, I can't say enough good things about them.
I think A&M was blessed with having very moral students.
I really don't think you have that as much today as we had it back then.
But they were really, really outstanding.
And I was always proud that Perry had a degree from A&M.
I was just sorry that
I wasn't able to get one, too, because when we lived in College View, if I could have just gotten my last year, it would have been fine, but it would have been great.
But we needed to get him out of school, so that was worth the sacrifice.
As she said, the students, they're my fondest memory of A&M, and they always were, and they always
always pretty upbeat, really.
And as the years went on, it began to change, and I guess the change started somewhere in 75, where it began to get worse.
And when I say worse, I mean the students and everything began to kind of come apart.
I guess the 60s influenced on it.
Well, it didn't come apart, but
The closeness, the cohesiveness of the student body began to change.
You retire in what year?
As you look back on those years,
What did it mean to you that you came to Texas A&M, to school?
Well, it means a whole hell of a lot, because I don't know, I wouldn't be where I am today.
If I had gone and went on back to Oklahoma A&M, now Oklahoma State, I don't know what I would have done.
Perry's people, Perry's father, he was
He was talking to you about his father.
That wasn't his father.
That was his mother.
His mother married.
But his father was a surgeon.
And all of the Perrys were in the medical field.
His aunt worked with Dr. Banning and Best to make insulin.
And they always thought Perry would go over to medical school.
But when he went to A&M, they just felt like disowning him because he was not going to do this.
But anyway, later on, as they came to visit us, they realized we hadn't gone to hell in a handbasket and everything was okay.

If somebody gave you today, this is the next last question, if somebody gave you today a check for a million dollars with only one condition on it, you must give it to Texas A&M, but you can decide what the money is going to be used for.
What would you tell them to use it for?
Most of it I would want to put in the scholarships.
Awarded on what basis?
on need, I think, not just their scholastic ability.
You know, with that much money, I might endow one presidential scholar.
And I put some into the, what is it, the fun for bricks and mortar that they're talking about.
Okay, last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart now for Texas A&M?
I love it.
I'm enjoying retirement, and I tell everybody when it stopped being fun, that's when I decided I'd retire.
Some people said, do you miss it?
And I said, you know, really, I'm still fortunate that I belong to a committee out there, ex-officio.
But I said, I don't have time to work anymore.
I've got other things going on.
But I don't, I miss the association with the students.
